text.headline: TimelineJS Media Types
text.text:
TimelineJS supports many media types. This provides a simple way to test them all. This page tests a simple image on a remote server. Also, if the Timeline was created with the soundcite option set to true then this should be an active SoundCite player.

click to jump to Wikipedia Images

media.caption: the Monkey section of David Van Tieghem's Ear Drums

text.headline: YouTube Videos
text.text:
if Timeline finds a URL that starts with 'youtube.com' or 'youtu.be', it will try to use it to embed a YouTube video. The protocol part of the URL (e.g. https://) is technically optional.

You can start at a specific point in the video using the t=#m#s parameter: see http://youtubetime.com/

text.headline: PNG image on Google Drive
text.text: To embed an image from Google Drive, just copy the Shareable link. Note that images embedded this way will appear within a Google Drive 'viewer', and so will look quite different from normally embedded images.

text.headline: PDF
text.text: A URL to a PDF will be inlined in an iFrame -- but the remote server must be configured to permit it.

text.headline: Audio
text.text: A URL to an audio file (mp3|wav|m4a) will be rendered using the browser's native audio player.

text.headline: Video (mp4)
text.text: A URL to a video file (mp4) will be rendered using the browser's native video player.

text.headline: Video (webm)
text.text: The Video media type also supports webm files.
